Presentation tier
The top-most level of the application
is the user interface. The main function
of the interface is to translate tasks
and results to something the user can
understand.
Logic tier
This layer coordinates the
application, processes commands,
makes logical decisions and
evaluations, and performs
calculations. It also moves and
processes data between the two
surrounding layers.
Data tier
Here information is stored and retrieved
from a database or file system. The
information is then passed back to the
logic tier for processing, and then
eventually back to the user.

N-Tier
Simple web applications
Migrating an on-premises application to cloud with minimal refactoring
‚Ä¢ Unified development of on-premises and cloud applications
Benefits
‚óè
‚óè
Ease of Portability
Less learning curve
Natural evolution from the traditional application model
Open to heterogeneous environments (Windows/Linux)
Challenges
Possibility of CRUD middle tier with extra latency without useful work
Monolithic design: Preventing independent deployment of features
Good for laaS (more work)
Difficult to manage network security in a large system
‚óè
Reference: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/architecture/
7

N-Tier: Best Practices
‚Ä¢ Use autoscaling to handle changes in load
‚Ä¢ Use asynchronous messaging to decouple tiers
‚óè
Cache semi-static data
‚óè
Configure the database tier for high availability
‚Ä¢ Place a web application firewall (WAF) between the front end and the Internet
‚Ä¢ Place each tier in its own subnet, and use subnets as a security boundary
‚Ä¢ Restrict access to the data tier, by allowing requests only from the middle tier(s)
Reference: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/architecture/

Web-Queue-Worker
‚Ä¢ For a purely PaaS Solution
‚óè
‚óè
‚óè
Benefits
‚óè
‚óè
When using managed services (PaaS or SaaS) rather than laaS
Batch operations, resource Intensive Tasks
Long workflows, simple domain
‚óè
Challenges
Potential of front end and the worker to become large monolithic components that are difficult to maintain & update
Possible hidden dependencies if the front end and worker share data schemas or code modules
‚óè
Simple architecture & easy to understand, deploy, and manage
Clear separation of concerns (front-end and worker)
Communicate using asynchronous messaging
Scaled independently
Reference: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/architecture/
10

Web-Queue-Worker: Best Practices
‚óè
‚óè
Expose a well-designed API to the client
Auto-scale to handle changes in load
‚Ä¢ Cache semi-static data
‚Ä¢ Use a CDN to host static content
‚óè
‚Ä¢ Use polyglot persistence when appropriate
‚Ä¢ Partition data to improve scalability, reduce contention, and optimize performance
Reference: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/architecture/

Event-Drive: Usage
‚óè
‚óè
‚óè
‚óè
Multiple subsystems must process the same events
Real-time processing with minimum time lag
Complex event processing, such as pattern matching or aggregation over time windows
High volume and high velocity of data, such as loT
Benefits
Producers & consumers are decoupled
‚Ä¢ No point-to-point integrations: Easy to add new consumers to the system
‚óè
‚óè
‚óè
‚óè
‚óè
Challenges
‚óè
Consumers can respond to events immediately as they arrive.
Highly scalable and distributed
Subsystems have independent views of the event stream
‚óè
Hard to ensure guaranteed delivery
Processing events in order or exactly once

Managing the volume of number crunching
